            <div class="description">
                <p>Minerals are inorganic substances required by the body in small amounts for a variety of different
                    functions. Minerals are involved in the formation of bones and teeth; they are essential
                    constituents of body fluids and tissues; they are components of enzyme systems and they are involved
                    in normal nerve function. The body requires different amounts of each mineral; people have different
                    requirements, according to their age, sex, physiological state (e.g. pregnancy) and sometimes their
                    state of health. The Department of Health has published Dietary Reference Values (DRVs) for minerals
                    for different groups of healthy people.</p>
            </div>
